💽 Disk Imaging & Forensic Analysis (Kali + Autopsy)

STEP 1: Open Terminal
• Open Kali Linux
• Press: Ctrl + Alt + T

STEP 2: Create Evidence File
• Run: echo "Cybersecurity Lab Evidence" > evidence.txt
• Verify: ls
• File evidence.txt created

STEP 3: Identify Disk
• Run: lsblk
• View disks like: sda, sda1
• sda = disk, sda1 = partition

STEP 4: Create Practice Disk
• Run: dd if=/dev/zero of=practice_disk.dd bs=1M count=100
• Creates 100 MB disk file

STEP 5: Format Disk
• Run: mkfs.ext4 practice_disk.dd
• Converts into EXT4 filesystem

STEP 6: Create Forensic Image
• Install tool: sudo apt install dc3dd
• Run: sudo dc3dd if=practice_disk.dd of=/home/kali/disk_image.dd hash=md5 log=/home/kali/acquisition.log
• Creates image + MD5 hash + log

STEP 7: Verify Image & Log
• Check image: ls -lh /home/kali/disk_image.dd
• Check log: cat /home/kali/acquisition.log

STEP 8: Start Autopsy
• Run: autopsy
• Open browser → http://localhost:9999/autopsy

STEP 9: Create New Case
• Click Create New Case
• Enter Case Name + Description
• Click Next

STEP 10: Add Host
• Enter Host Name
• Add description
• Click Next

STEP 11: Add Disk Image
• Click Add Image
• Select /home/kali/disk_image.dd
• Click Next → Finish

STEP 12: Analyze Evidence
• Go to File Analysis
• Search: evidence.txt
• File will be found
